The paper deals with the problem of computing a longest increasing subsequence in the presence of errors, which is a fundamental problem in computer science and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The use of probabilistic analysis and approximation algorithms suggests that the paper may also be relevant to information theory (cs.IT) and computational complexity (cs.CC). The study of lower bounds and the analysis of the performance of algorithms on random sequences suggest that the paper may also be relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and machine learning (cs.LG).
